<p begin="00:32:42.060" end="00:32:49.460" style="s2">“wants” as having some sort of high status<br />that everything has to be evaluated in terms</p>
<p begin="00:32:49.460" end="00:32:50.460" style="s2">of?</p>
<p begin="00:32:50.460" end="00:32:51.460" style="s2">Uh huh.</p>
<p begin="00:32:51.460" end="00:32:54.760" style="s2">And then philosophically we say: Where do<br />“wants” come from? And of course there’s</p>
<p begin="00:32:54.760" end="00:33:01.100" style="s2">a long anthropological and psychological set<br />of literature here. What’s the source of</p>
<p begin="00:33:01.100" end="00:33:06.890" style="s2">our “wants”? Are they based in biological<br />drives? Are they instinctual? Are they acquired?</p>
<p begin="00:33:06.890" end="00:33:13.060" style="s2">Are they intellectual? Do they have any relationship<br />to our rational capacities? When I&#39;m acting,</p>
<p begin="00:33:13.060" end="00:33:17.320" style="s2">should I act on my desires and my wants, and<br />so forth?</p>
<p begin="00:33:17.320" end="00:33:22.900" style="s2">So there’s that whole tradition, and we<br />have to have a sophisticated theory about</p>
<p begin="00:33:22.900" end="00:33:27.580" style="s2">how all of that is going to work if we’re<br />going to say we’ll solve all of these cognitive</p>
