<p begin="00:33:32.850" end="00:33:38.070" style="s2">“achievement of goals” the way pragmatists<br />want us to do.</p>
<p begin="00:33:38.070" end="00:33:43.400" style="s2">And again, it’s fairly easy to imagine what<br />the skeptical argument is likely going to</p>
<p begin="00:33:43.400" end="00:33:47.810" style="s2">be. If it’s a matter of what I want—well,<br />isn’t science supposed to be about coming</p>
<p begin="00:33:47.810" end="00:33:52.320" style="s2">up with general truths or maybe even universal<br />truths?</p>
<p begin="00:33:52.320" end="00:33:53.320" style="s2">Okay …</p>
<p begin="00:33:53.320" end="00:33:56.590" style="s2">And if it’s immediately going to devolve<br />into whatever individuals want, well then</p>
<p begin="00:33:56.590" end="00:33:58.730" style="s2">we’re going to go in fairly scattered directions.</p>
<p begin="00:33:58.730" end="00:34:05.140" style="s2">Okay, so that also opens up a good point for<br />a segue into the potential link between Neo-Marxism,</p>
<p begin="00:34:05.140" end="00:34:07.400" style="s2">let’s say, and Postmodernism.</p>
<p begin="00:34:07.400" end="00:34:08.400" style="s2">Sure.</p>
<p begin="00:34:08.400" end="00:34:14.710" style="s2">Because maybe you could say: Once you&#39;ve opened<br />the door to an admission that you can criticize</p>
<p begin="00:34:14.710" end="00:34:19.520" style="s2">the idea of “want” as a social construct,<br />let’s say—which is one of the things that</p>
